What is a hash?
A hash is a one-way function. You put in "hello123" and get out "482c811da5d5b4bc6d497ffa98491e38". You cannot reverse it. But if you hash the same word twice, you get the same result,
that's how password checking works. We try every word in the wordlist, hash it, and see if it matches.

Dictionary Attack
We read rockyou.txt line by line, hash each word with MD5/SHA1/SHA256, and compare it to the target hash. If it matches, cracked. This is the most common real-world attack technique.

Entropy -> the math behind password strength
Entropy = log2(charset_size ^ length). A 4-digit PIN uses charset 10 (0–9), so 10^4 = 10,000 possibilities = 13.3 bits of entropy. 
The longer and more varied the charset (uppercase + lowercase + numbers + symbols), the exponentially harder to crack. We score passwords using this formula.

Crack Time Estimation
MD5 can be computed ~10 billion times/second on a GPU. SHA-256 ~2 billion/sec. bcrypt is intentionally slow — ~10,000/sec. 
We divide the total keyspace by the attack speed to estimate crack time in seconds, minutes, years.

